faqSchema:
  - question: "What is a Self-Directed Brokerage Account (SDBA)?"
    answer: "Quick answer: A Self-Directed Brokerage Account (SDBA) is a feature inside many 401(k), 403(b), 457, and TSP plans that lets participants invest in thousands of mutual funds and ETFs beyond the plan's standard fund lineup — same tax treatment, same match. Think of it as a brokerage window inside your retirement plan — same tax treatment, same employer match, dramatically more investment options."
  - question: "Does my retirement plan offer an SDBA?"
    answer: "Many mid-to-large employers and the federal TSP do — but plans rarely advertise it. Common SDBA platforms include Fidelity BrokerageLink, Schwab Personal Choice Retirement Account (PCRA), Empower Brokerage, and Vanguard Brokerage Option. A Capital Wealth advisor can confirm your plan's eligibility on a complimentary 30-minute call."
  - question: "Who is eligible to use an SDBA?"
    answer: "If your employer plan offers an SDBA, every active participant is generally eligible regardless of income, job title, or investment experience. You don't have to be a senior executive or a high-net-worth investor to use it."
  - question: "Does my money leave my employer's 401(k) plan?"
    answer: "No. This is one of the most important things to understand about an SDBA — your money never leaves your 401(k). The brokerage window is an account inside your existing plan. You keep your employer match, your pre-tax or Roth tax treatment, and your ERISA creditor protections. There's no rollover, no distribution, and no taxable event."
  - question: "How is an SDBA different from a target-date fund?"
    answer: "Target-date funds assume every participant of a given age has the same savings, the same risk tolerance, the same outside assets, and the same tax picture — which simply isn't true. A professionally managed SDBA lets us build an allocation around your actual timeline, your other accounts (IRAs, taxable brokerage, your spouse's plan), and your risk comfort, and then monitor it in real time."
  - question: "Can my financial advisor manage my SDBA?"
    answer: "Yes — that's exactly what we do. Most advisors can't access your workplace plan, which is why so many 401(k)s sit unmanaged. The SDBA creates a bridge that lets Capital Wealth professionally manage your retirement plan investments alongside your IRAs and taxable accounts as one coordinated portfolio."
  - question: "How much does an SDBA cost?"
    answer: "Plan providers typically charge a small annual SDBA account fee (often $25-$50), plus fund expense ratios and any trading costs. Many investors are surprised that this is less than the hidden expense ratios of their default target-date fund. Capital Wealth's advisory fee is transparent, disclosed upfront, and billed directly against the SDBA — never as a hidden commission inside a fund."
  - question: "What does 'fiduciary' mean here?"
    answer: "Capital Wealth Advisors is a State of Utah Registered Investment Advisor. As a fiduciary, we are legally required to put your interests ahead of our own and disclose any conflicts of interest. We don't earn commissions on fund selections — our only incentive is managing your account responsibly over time."
  - question: "How often is the account reviewed or rebalanced?"
    answer: "Continuously. We monitor portfolios in real time and rebalance when markets, your risk profile, or your plan circumstances change — not on a 'set it and forget it' schedule. We also coach semi-annually as life events (raises, kids, job changes, home purchases) reshape your plan."
  - question: "Is my money protected inside an SDBA?"
    answer: "Yes. Your funds stay inside your employer-sponsored 401(k), so they retain all of the plan's protections — including ERISA creditor protection in most cases. Nothing is withdrawn or moved outside your employer's retirement plan."
  - question: "Can I see my SDBA on my normal 401(k) statement?"
    answer: "Yes. Your brokerage window balance appears alongside your core account on a consolidated statement, and you can view both online through your plan provider (Fidelity, Schwab, Empower, Vanguard, TIAA, etc.). Specific features vary by platform."
  - question: "Can I roll in prior-employer 401(k)s?"
    answer: "In most cases, yes. Rollovers from previous employer plans into your current 401(k) are generally allowed and can simplify your picture dramatically. We'll walk through the tradeoffs on your call — sometimes consolidating in is best, sometimes leaving balances elsewhere (or moving to an IRA) is the better choice."
  - question: "What happens to my SDBA if I leave my job?"
    answer: "You generally have four options: leave the balance in your former employer's plan, roll it into your new employer's 401(k), roll it into an IRA, or take a distribution (usually not recommended due to taxes and penalties). Each has different implications for fees, investment options, creditor protection, and ongoing advice. We'll help you weigh them when the time comes."
  - question: "What are the 2026 401(k) contribution limits?"
    answer: "For the 2026 tax year, the IRS limit for employee contributions to a traditional or Roth 401(k) (or a combination) is $24,500. Participants age 50 and older can add an $8,000 catch-up for a total of $32,500. Under SECURE 2.0, participants ages 60–63 may contribute an additional $11,250 'super catch-up' where the plan allows, for a combined total of $34,750. Employer match and profit-sharing are on top of those limits."
  - question: "Can I stop SDBA management later?"
    answer: "Yes. You can discontinue the advisory engagement at any time, subject to your plan's rules. Your money stays in your 401(k) throughout — nothing is taken out of your employer plan."
  - question: "Do I still control my 401(k) if Capital Wealth manages my SDBA?"
    answer: "Yes. You retain full control of your 401(k) account and plan participation. Capital Wealth manages the investment selection inside the Self-Directed Brokerage Account as your fiduciary — you can pause, modify, or cancel SDBA management at any time without affecting the rest of your 401(k)."
  - question: "Can I see my SDBA in my regular 401(k) account online?"
    answer: "Yes. Your SDBA appears as an investment position inside your normal 401(k) or TSP online account. For detailed holdings, you can also log in directly to the brokerage platform (Fidelity, Schwab, Empower, Vanguard, or TSP) that powers the SDBA."
  - question: "How do I know which investments are right for me inside an SDBA?"
    answer: "Your Capital Wealth fiduciary advisor builds your SDBA portfolio around your age, retirement timeline, risk tolerance, existing assets, and income needs. Selection and ongoing rebalancing are handled for you — no DIY fund-picking required."
